### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

forms

### Description

I want to be notified each time a user touches a field so I have more control over the timing of value or status change emissions without changing the control update strategy to 'onblur'.

```ts
const control = new FormControl()

control.valuesChanges.pipe(
  audit(() => control.events.pipe(filter(event => event instanceof TouchedEvent))),
).subscribe((value) => {
  // Do something with the value each time the user touched the field.
})
```

This would also be useful for delegating control value accessors to a reactive form control

```ts
// CVA host directive
@Directive({ standalone: true })
class MyValueAccessor implements ControlValueAccessor {
  // Use this in component template
  control = new FormControl()

  writeValue(value) {
    this.control.setValue(value)
  }

  registerOnChange(fn) {
    this.onChange = fn
  }

  registerOnTouched(fn) {
    this.onTouched = fn
  }

  next(event: ControlEvent) {
    if (event instanceof ValueChangeEvent) {
      this.onChange?.(event.source.value)
    }
    if (event instanceof TouchedEvent) {
      this.onTouched?.()
    }
  }

  constructor() {
    this.control.events.subscribe(this)
  }
}
```

### Proposed solution

Add a new event type `TouchedEvent` that is similar to `TouchedChangeEvent` except it emits every time the user "touched" a field, irrespective of the touched state.

### Alternatives considered

For now I am decorating `markAsTouched` to create a stream of touch events.

```ts
const touchedEvents = new Subject()
const control = new FormControl()
const markAsTouched = control.markAsTouched
control.markAsTouched = function (opts) {
  markAsTouched.call(this, opts)
  touchedEvents.next({ source: this })
}
```

### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

### Description

When using a signal in the template, it would be beneficial if the null check is considered for the accessor, reducing the need for repetitive null checks when accessing properties of the object.

**Use Case:**
Consider the following scenario in an Angular component where a Person object is accessed:

```
import { Component, signal } from '@angular/core';
import { bootstrapApplication } from '@angular/platform-browser';
import 'zone.js';

interface Person {
  name: string;
}
@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  standalone: true,
  template: `
    <h1>Hello from {{ name }}!</h1>
    <div>
      @if(person()) {
        {{ person().name }}
      }
    </div>
  `,
})
export class App {
  name = 'Angular';
  person = signal<null | Person>(null);


}

bootstrapApplication(App);
```

Right now the @if expression already checks if the person is defined. Therefore I would expect that the person().name expression just works but it is still considered as possibly null. Of course, you could handle this using an @if (person() as personDefined) expression but there are some use cases where it would be easier to just check before if a variable is defined and then access the variable. 
 
The error is the following:
![image](https://github.com/angular/angular/assets/46619772/0e42eeea-e9b7-41c2-b345-0ea657a4c0b6)


Example URL: https://stackblitz.com/edit/stackblitz-starters-zs2wwy?file=src%2Fmain.ts


### Proposed solution

If a signal is checked against null it is not considered as potentially null inside the if statement. 

### Alternatives considered

Probably a structural let directive or something like that would also help in this matter. But in the end a typesafe check should already be enough.

